The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Wednesday, January 07, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		Two persons were arrested in Bihar by sleuths from the detective department of Calcutta Police. They were picked up on charges of firing at Shova Agarwal, wife of the owner of a fast-food chain in the city, at Kankurgachhi. According to deputy commissioner, detective department, Soumen Mitra, the accused, identified as Amit and Chhotu Singh, will be brought to Calcutta soon.																																																		A division bench of Calcutta High Court rejected an anticipatory bail plea of Mohan Jadav, a resident of Sankrail, in Howrah, on Tuesday. Jadav is apprehending arrest in connection with the seizure of several machines used to manufacture five-rupee coins. A few days ago, police arrested two of his associates while he managed to escape. State public prosecutor Kaji Safarulla also informed the court that apart from manufacturing coins, Jadav used to sell coin-manufacturing machines for Rs 1 lakh.																																																		State labour minister Mohammad Amin said he would meet members of all 15 workers unions regarding the strike in state jute factories on Wednesday, at Writers Buildings. On Thursday, Amin will meet the owners of the factories. Later, he will hold a tripartite meeting involving the factory owners and the union members, if the separate sessions with each prove fruitful. According to the minister, a shift in stance is essential on both sides for a solution.																																																		Health department officials of Howrah admitted that they could not attain 100 per cent success in administering polio vaccines, especially in the rural areas. According to Majed Mollah, member of the district zilla parishad, at least 250 children were not allowed to take the dose of pulse polio by their parents in Bardanga, Munshipara and Damodarpur, of Uluberia, Block I, due to lack of awareness.																																																		S.B. Purkayastha, director (administration), of the Advanced Medical Research Institute (AMRI) Hospitals, announced on Tuesday that the hospitals would start their alternative medicine clinics in January. Purkayastha said these will include obesity, well-being and stress-relief clinics. The treatment provided will have no side-effects, he added.																																																		A 25-year-old housewife, Khairul Nisha, suffered serious burns on Tuesday afternoon in her home in Bibi Bazar slum, in the Cossipore police station area, when the stove she was cooking on exploded. According to police, she was admitted to RG Kar Hospital.																																																		The 15th annual book fair in Howrah will start on January 10 at Howrah Maidan.  To Churu Nagarik Parishad for  distributing Jaipur feet and calipers among the polio-affected,  free of cost
